50|$|In {{parliamentary}} procedure using Robert's Rules of Order, {{the wording}} of a motion could be changed by an <b>amendment.</b> This <b>amendment</b> <b>is</b> called a primary amendment, or first-degree amendment. A secondary amendment, or second-degree <b>amendment</b> <b>is</b> an <b>amendment</b> of an <b>amendment.</b> Secondary <b>amendments</b> <b>are</b> handled like other amendments in {{that they can be}} debated and voted on before moving forward.|$|R
50|$|In {{parliamentary}} procedure, {{a friendly}} <b>amendment</b> <b>is</b> an <b>amendment</b> to a motion under debate that is perceived by all parties as an enhancement {{to the original}} motion, often only as clarification of intent. However, these <b>amendments</b> <b>are</b> {{to be treated like}} other amendments.|$|R
