5|$|On June 18, 1866, Congress {{adopted the}} Fourteenth Amendment, which {{guaranteed}} citizenship and equal {{protection under the}} laws regardless of race, {{and sent it to}} the states for ratification. After a bitter struggle that included attempted rescissions of ratification by two states, the Fourteenth <b>Amendment</b> <b>was</b> adopted on July 28, 1868.|$|E
5|$|The <b>amendment</b> <b>was</b> {{proposed}} by the 62nd Congress in 1912 and adopted in 1913 upon being ratified by three-fourths (36) of the state legislatures. It was first implemented in special elections in Maryland (November 1913) and Alabama (May 1914), then nationwide in the November 1914 election.|$|E
